You have spotted a very common and dangerous mistake in multi-threaded programming!
Whether the locking mechanism works depends entirely on how many Display objects you create in your main method.
1. When it WORKS (Shared Object)
If you create one Display object and pass it to both threads, it works perfectly.
 * Why? Both threads are looking at the exact same lock instance inside that single Display object. When Thread A grabs the key, Thread B sees that the door is locked because they are standing at the same door.
Display commonDisplay = new Display(); // Only ONE lock created here
Thread t1 = new Thread(new WishTask(commonDisplay, "Dhoni"));
Thread t2 = new Thread(new WishTask(commonDisplay, "Yuvraj"));

2. When it FAILS (Separate Objects)
If you create two Display objects, the locking mechanism will not work. Each thread will print "Good Morning" at the same time, and the output will be jumbled.
 * Why? Each new Display() creates a new ReentrantLock.
 * Thread A grabs the key to Lock A.
 * Thread B grabs the key to Lock B.
 * Since they are using different keys for different doors, they both enter their respective wish methods simultaneously. They don't even know the other thread exists!
// ERROR: Two different locks created!
Thread t1 = new Thread(new WishTask(new Display(), "Dhoni")); 
Thread t2 = new Thread(new WishTask(new Display(), "Yuvraj"));

3. How to make the Lock "Global" (The static Fix)
If you want the locking to work even if someone creates multiple Display objects, you must make the lock static.
A static variable belongs to the Class, not the individual object. There will only be one lock for the entire application, no matter how many times you call new Display().
class Display {
    // Adding 'static' makes this a "Global" lock for all Display objects
    private static final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void wish(String name) {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            // ... loop logic ...
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}

Summary Comparison
| Lock Type | Logic | Result |
|---|---|---|
| Instance Lock (No static) | private final Lock lock | Works ONLY if threads share one Display object. |
| Class Lock (static) | private static final Lock lock | Works ALWAYS, even if threads have different Display objects. |
